vectorData.altText: 24. The _______ is a recess that surrounds the cervix at its junction with the vagina.

The body of the uterus is anteflexed      relative to the cervix, and comes to lie superior to the bladder. The cervix itself is anteverted      relative to the vagina. 
The thick wall of the cervix bulges into the proximal end of the thin-walled vaginal canal. The recess where the cervix is continuous with the wall of the vagina is the vaginal fornix.
The uterine cavity is continuous with the cervical canal at the internal os     and the cervical canal is continuous with the vaginal canal at the external os.
The anterior wall of the vagina lies adjacent to the base of the bladder and urethra     . The vagina and urethra pass from the pelvis, through the pelvic floor to the perineum, where both structures open into the vestibule.
The posterior wall of the vagina lies adjacent to the rectum, separated by the rectovaginal septum.
The junction between the thick-walled cervix and thin-walled vagina creates a ring-like recess around the margin of the cervix called the vaginal fornix. 
Because the vaginal canal is normally collapsed, a physician uses a speculum to open the vagina in order to view the cervix, fornix and external os (see lower figure).
arched or bent forward; the uterus is bent forward at the junction of its body and cervix
a position that is pivoted, or tilted, forward relative to the position of another structure; the cervix of the uterus tilts forward relative to the vagina.
That’s right! The vaginal fornix surrounds the cervix.
